{{Moresources|date=February 2015}} {{Infobox Ambassador | honorific-prefix = | name = Haron Amin | honorific-suffix = | image = Haron Amin, Spokesman Northern Allience, Afghanistan.jpg | imagesize = 150px | caption = Mohammad Haron Amin in 2001 | order = | ambassador_from = Afghan | country = Japan | term_start = April 30, 2004 | term_end = April 30, 2009 | predecessor = | successor = [[Eklil Ahmad Hakimi]] | president = [[Hamid Karzai]] | birthname = Mohammad Haron Amin | birth_date = July 19, 1969<ref>Some sources cite 1967.</ref> | birth_place = [[Kabul|Kabul, Afghanistan]] | death_date = February 15, 2015 | death_place = [[Phoenix, Arizona]], United States}}
'''Mohammad Haron Amin''' ([[Dari (Persian dialect)|Dari]]: هارون امین&lrm;; July 19, 1969<ref>Some sources cite 1967.</ref> – February 15, 2015) was the [[Afghanistan|Afghan]] [[ambassador]] to [[Japan]] {{citation needed span|text=and non-resident ambassador to [[Thailand]], [[the Philippines]] and [[Singapore]]|date=February 2017}} from 2004-09. He is chiefly known, however, for his role as spokesman for the [[Northern Alliance]] during the [[United States|U.S.]]-led invasion of his country after the events of [[September 11, 2001]].<ref name="Afghan Bios">[http://www.afghan-bios.info/index.php?option=com_afghanbios&id=646&task=view&total=3403&start=297&Itemid=2 Profile], Afghan-bios.info, November 2, 2009.</ref>
A consistent presence in American media prior to the [[Taliban]]'s collapse,<ref>{{cite news|title=Amin: Northern Alliance will support U.S.|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2001/WORLD/asiapcf/central/09/22/amin.afghanistan.access.cnna|accessdate=February 15, 2015|publisher=CNN.com|date=September 22, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Alliance Advances|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/asia-july-dec01-alliance_11-12|accessdate=February 15, 2015|agency=PBS|date=November 12, 2001}}</ref> Amin was appointed [[chargé d'affaires]] to the United States by the interim Afghan government on January 14, 2002, led by [[Hamid Karzai]]. He was the highest-ranking Afghan diplomat in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] for a year-long period in 2002-03, before being appointed by President Karzai as his country's first [http://www.afghan-web.com/bios/haroon_amin.html Ambassador to Japan] on 30 April 2004.<ref name=afghanembassy/>
Born in [[Kabul]],<ref name=afghanembassy>{{cite news|title=Profile: Haron Amin|url=http://www.afghanembassyjp.com/ambassadorbioc.html|accessdate=February 15, 2015|publisher=Embassy of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan in Tokyo|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819161513/http://www.afghanembassyjp.com/ambassadorbioc.html|archivedate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> his [[Tajik people|Tajik]] family fled Afghanistan one year after the [[Soviet war in Afghanistan|Soviet invasion of 1979]], eventually settling in the U.S.<ref name="Afghan Bios"/>
He returned to his home country in 1988 to fight with the [[mujahideen]] under their commander [[Ahmed Shah Massoud]], who assigned Amin to Afghanistan's embassy in Washington in 1990. Amin worked for the foreign ministry in various capacities until the government's fall to the Taliban in 1996.<ref>[http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/culture/features/5298/index2.html Profile], nymag.com; accessed February 25, 2017.</ref> At the time of the 9/11 attacks, Amin was serving as a diplomat of the Afghan mission to the [[United Nations]].{{cn|date=April 2018}}
Amin was distinguished in 2002 as one of 77 "People for the Future" in ''[[Newsweek]]''.<ref name="tolo"/> He earned a [[master's degree]] in political science from [[St. John's University (New York)|St. John's University]] in 2005, and later earned a Certificate of International Law in the school's Master's Program.<ref name=afghanembassy/>
In 2007, drawing from his years in Japan, he wrote ''Afghan-Japan Relations: Lands Under the Rising Sun''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Amin|first1=Haron|title=Afghan-Japan Relations: Land Under the Rising Sun|url=http://www.afghanembassyjp.com/pdf/afghanjapanrelations/afghanjapanrelations.pdf|accessdate=February 15, 2015|agency=Embassy of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan in Tokyo|date=2007}}</ref> The book centers on historical relations and similarities between Japan and Afghanistan, and is the first to directly compare Afghanistan's and Japan's past and cultural heritage.<ref name="tolo"/>
==Awards== * Freedom, Faith and Hope Medal, Georgetown University, USA (2002)<ref name=afghanembassy/> * President's Medal, La Salle University, USA (2002)<ref name=afghanembassy/>
==Death== Amin died of cancer, which had been first diagnosed in 2011, in a [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]-area hospital, on February 14, 2015.<ref name="tolo">{{cite news|title=Former Afghan Diplomat and Ambassador to Japan Dies|url=http://www.tolonews.com/afghanistan/former-afghan-diplomat-and-ambassador-japan-dies-46|accessdate=February 15, 2015|work=TOLO News|date=February 15, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215204921/http://www.tolonews.com/en/afghanistan/18221-former-afghan-diplomat-and-ambassador-to-japan-dies-at-46|archivedate=February 15, 2015}}</ref>
